Google Play Apps Review Prediction using Random Forest Regression

Lesson Goals¶

In this lesson, we will learn exploratory data analysis using Seaborn and matplotlib library and we also predict app reviews using Random forest Regression technique.

def filter(per):
    if "M" in str(per) and "," in str(per):
        per = str(per).replace("M","")
        per = per.replace(",","")
        return int(per)*1000000
    elif "M" in str(per):
        per = int(str(per).replace("M",""))
        return per*1000000
    elif "," in str(per):
        per = str(per).replace(",","")
        return int(per)
    
    else:  
        return int(per)
In [12]:
data["Reviews"] =data["Reviews"].apply(filter) # all the values of column 'Reviews' are passed to filter method

def filter1(per):
    per = str(per)
    if "M" in per:
        per = per.replace("M","")
        return float(per)
    elif per == "Varies with device":
        return np.NaN
    elif "k" in per:
        return float(per.replace("k",""))/1000
    else:
        return float(per)
In [59]:
def filter2(per):
    per = str(per)
    if "+" in per:
        per = per.replace("+","")
    if "," in per:
        per = per.replace(",","")
        
    return int(per)

def filter3(per):
    per = str(per)
    if "$" in per:
        per=per.split("$")[1]
    return (float(per)*69.44)

In [84]:
mldata = data[["Reviews","Size","Installs","Price","Rating"]]
mldata.dropna(inplace=True)

X=mldata.iloc[:,0:-1].values
y = mldata.iloc[:,-1].values

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
xtrain,xtest,ytrain,ytest = train_test_split(X,y)

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
rfr = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=300)

Summary¶

In this tutorial, you discovered how to explore data using seaborn and matplotlib library and predict app reviews using random forest techniques.

Specifically, you learned:

How to filter the data using numpy. How to visualize data using seaborn. How to manupulate graph using plotly . How to predict review using sklearn module.
